WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.880
So we had published a while ago the group that can increase the risk of de novo AML.

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:19.660
And if you look at the pre-malignant patterns for de novo AML, you see a very varied pattern.

00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:28.180
TP53 is there, but a lot of it are the de novo mutations, TET2, DNMG3A, RONC, and IDH.

00:00:28.860 --> 00:00:34.000
These patterns are different than what we are seeing in therapy-related myeloid neoplasms.

00:00:35.720 --> 00:00:41.900
So when we think about predicting myeloid neoplasms, and I talked yesterday about all

00:00:41.900 --> 00:00:47.580
of the scoring criteria, I want to point out that none of them are validated for therapy-related

00:00:47.580 --> 00:00:51.880
myeloid neoplasms or in the setting of selective pressures from chemotherapy,

00:00:52.300 --> 00:00:57.720
radiation, and other small molecules. So we cannot use these for prediction

00:00:57.720 --> 00:01:05.140
risk. We also know from long-term population studies, this is our work from the Women's

00:01:05.140 --> 00:01:10.740
Health Initiative, that the median doubling time of mutations in the absence of chemotherapy is

00:01:10.740 --> 00:01:17.060
almost seven years. So these are slow-growing mutations. When you see a rapid rise in clone

00:01:17.060 --> 00:01:26.580
size in the setting of selective pressure, this is clearly different and more predictive of our

00:01:26.580 --> 00:01:35.660
therapy-related diseases. So if you think about then what causes therapy-related myeloid neoplasms,

00:01:35.720 --> 00:01:41.800
there's two scenarios. That age-related CH is present at baseline, and because of selective

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:47.180
pressures, there's expansion of these clones, ultimately leading to therapy-related myeloid

00:01:47.180 --> 00:01:55.900
neoplasms in certain individuals. Or there is a direct toxicity and DNA damage leading to

00:01:55.900 --> 00:01:56.560
new myeloid neoplasms. So there's a direct toxicity and DNA damage leading to new myeloid neoplasms.

